## SECTION 2 - SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE OVERVIEW

### **2.1 Architectural Layers**
The system is composed of six discrete layers. Each layer has a single responsibility and communicates with adjacent layers through well-defined contracts. No layer can bypass the one above it.

| **Layer** | **Name**        | **Components**                                                              | **Contract**                                                                               |
| --------- | --------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| L0        | User Interface  | Next.js Dashboard, WebSocket stream, Kill Switch panel                      | Emits signed task payloads to L1; receives telemetry SSE stream                            |
| L1        | Orchestrator    | DAG Engine, Task Scheduler, Persona Router, Checkpoint Manager              | Accepts task payload; owns DAG state; routes to L2 agents; writes checkpoints              |
| L2        | Persona Agents  | 10 specialized sub-agents (see Section 5)                                   | Receives typed task + context; returns structured `AgentResult` with action, diff, status    |
| L3        | Critic & Safety | Schema Validator, Diff Auditor, Rollback Controller, Action Classifier      | Blocks/approves L2 outputs; triggers rollback; escalates to human if CRITICAL+uncertain |
| L4        | Execution       | MCP Server, Actuators, Sandbox Runner, Filesystem Snapshot                  | Executes approved diffs; returns execution receipt with checksum; triggers L3 verify pass  |
| L5        | Persistence     | SQLite (DAG + checkpoints), ChromaDB (embeddings), Redis (rate limits, TTL) | Durable state for all layers; crash-safe via WAL; no in-memory-only state                  |

### **2.2 Action Classification Tiers**
Not every action deserves the full critic pipeline. The Action Classifier assigns one of three tiers before routing, cutting median latency by 60% for routine operations.

| **Tier** | **Label** | **Examples**                                                                   | **Pipeline**                                                                                     | **Max Latency**      |
| -------- | --------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | -------------------- |
| T1       | **TRIVIAL**   | Read file, list directory, web search, status check                            | Schema validation only → execute                                                                 | < 2s                 |
| T2       | **STANDARD**  | Write file, run test, call external API, install package                       | Schema → Diff dry-run → Critic approve → execute → verify                                        | < 15s                |
| T3       | **CRITICAL**  | Delete data, deploy to prod, modify .env, schema migration, destructive op | Full pipeline + snapshot + human escalation if uncertain + dual-checksum verify + rollback-ready | < 60s or human-gated |

