## SECTION 3 - MEMORY, PERSISTENCE & CONTEXT MANAGEMENT

### **3.1 Memory Architecture - Four Distinct Stores**
| **Store**              | **Backend**                   | **Contents**                                                                                                                               | **Eviction Policy**                         | **Crash Safe**         |
| ---------------------- | ----------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------- | ---------------------- |
| **Hard Anchors**           | SQLite table: `anchors`         | Absolute constraints tagged at session init (e.g. "never delete .env"). Read on every agent invocation.                                    | Never evicted. Manual delete only.          | Yes (WAL)              |
| **DAG Task State**         | SQLite table: `tasks`           | Task ID, status, assigned_persona, time_started, max_ttl, parent_task_ids, checkpoint_hash                                                 | Completed tasks archived after 7 days.      | Yes (WAL)              |
| **Conversational Context** | In-memory ring buffer (Redis) | Last N=20 turns per session. Summarized to 3-sentence digest every 10 turns by Rimuru agent.                                               | LRU; oldest turns summarized then dropped.  | Redis AOF              |
| **Failure Memory**         | ChromaDB collection: `failures` | Error message + stack trace embedded via `all-MiniLM-L6-v2`. Cosine similarity search at >= 0.82 blocks repeat errors. | Manual review required to purge.            | Yes (ChromaDB persist) |
| **Research Cache**         | SQLite + ChromaDB             | Trust-scored web research blocks. Semantic dedup before insertion.                                                                         | TTL = 24h for volatile topics, 7d for docs. | Yes                    |

### **3.2 Context Rolling with Hard Anchors**
Every agent invocation assembles context in this exact order. The order is enforced by the `ContextAssembler` class and cannot be overridden by agent output.

> **ANCHOR BLOCK (always first, never summarized)**
> `[SYSTEM ANCHORS]`
> - Never delete .env or .env.* files 
> - Never push to main branch directly 
> - Never expose secrets in logs 
> - Always run tests before marking task RESOLVED 
> `[END ANCHORS]`

After anchors: compressed session summary (3 sentences) → last 5 task receipts → current task → agent system prompt. Total context budget enforced at 80% of model `max_tokens` to preserve output space.

### **3.3 TTL-Aware Task Watchdog**
A background thread (`TTLWatchdog`) polls the tasks table every 30 seconds. If `now() - time_started > max_ttl` for any `IN_PROGRESS` task, the watchdog emits SIGTERM to the agent process, marks the task `TIMED_OUT`, and creates a new task node with status `NEEDS_REROUTE`. 

> **TTL Defaults by Persona Tier:**
> - Research agents (Doraemon, Rimuru): 300s 
> - Code agents (Naruto, Natsu, Goku): 600s 
> - Security agents (Ichigo): 180s 
> - Sandbox/Critic agents (Itachi): 120s 
> - Orchestrator tasks (Madara): **no TTL** (orchestrator manages its own watchdog)

